<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does walk-in cooler repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our commercial diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most walk-in cooler repairs run between $200 and $600. A door gasket, evaporator fan motor, thermostat, or defrost component is toward the lower end. Compressor replacement or refrigerant work runs significantly higher — we provide a full written estimate before any work begins, including an honest repair vs. replace assessment."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My walk-in cooler is not holding temperature — what should I do right now?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "First, check the door seal — a compromised gasket is the most common and least obvious cause of temperature drift. Close the door and watch for condensation or frost forming around the frame. Second, check the condenser coils (usually accessible from outside the cooler box) for dust and debris buildup. Third, if the unit is above 41°F, move your most temperature-sensitive inventory immediately — FDA food safety threshold is 41°F for cold storage. Then call us: (323) 870-4790. We treat refrigeration failures as priority commercial calls."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does my walk-in cooler keep icing up inside?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Excessive ice or frost inside a walk-in cooler almost always means the defrost system isn't running correctly. The evaporator coils defrost on a schedule — when the defrost heater, defrost timer, or defrost thermostat fails, frost accumulates until the coils are completely blocked and airflow stops. A door seal failure that allows warm, humid outside air to enter continuously is the secondary cause — particularly common in LA where humidity fluctuates seasonally."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My walk-in cooler motor is running constantly — what does that mean?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A compressor or evaporator fan that runs without cycling off is working against a thermal load it can't overcome. Most common causes: refrigerant leak (the system can't reach set temperature regardless of how long it runs), heavily frosted evaporator coils blocking airflow, dirty condenser coils preventing heat rejection, or a door that isn't sealing correctly. In LA's warm ambient temperatures, any of these push a marginal system over its limit faster than in cooler climates."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should a walk-in cooler be serviced in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Twice a year minimum — once before summer when ambient temperatures peak, and once before the holiday season when the cooler will be under maximum load. A service visit includes condenser coil cleaning (critical in LA's dusty, warm environment), evaporator inspection, door gasket check, refrigerant level verification, drain line clearing, and temperature calibration. Businesses in high-use environments like Koreatown restaurants or ghost kitchen facilities should consider quarterly service."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair all walk-in cooler brands?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. We service True, Turbo Air, Beverage-Air, Hoshizaki, Traulsen, Master-Bilt, Norlake, Kolpak, and most other commercial walk-in cooler brands and panel systems. We're EPA 608 certified for refrigerant handling and carry common parts for True and Turbo Air specifically. For older units or unusual configurations, we'll confirm parts availability before scheduling."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I repair or replace my walk-in cooler?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Walk-in coolers last 15–20 years with proper maintenance. If your unit is under 10 years old, repair almost always makes financial sense unless the compressor has failed on a poorly maintained system. If it's over 15 years old and needs a compressor, the calculation changes — we'll give you an honest assessment of expected remaining life before recommending a major repair. The cost of a new walk-in installation far exceeds most repair scenarios, which is why repair is usually the right call."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

